Do the drugs, do the time?
The Effect of Drug Abuse on Sentences Imposed on Drug Offenders in Three U.S. District Courts
Cassia Spohn
Arizona State University
Steven Belenko
Temple University
The purpose of this study is to determine whether offenders’ history of hard drug use and hard drug use at the time of the crime affect case outcomes for offenders in three federal district courts. We focus on three outcomes—whether the offender was in pretrial detention prior to adjudication, whether the offender received a downward departure for providing substantial assistance, and the length of the sentence imposed on offenders who were sentenced to prison—and we hypothesize that the offender’s history of drug use and drug use at the time of the crime will have varying effects on the three outcomes. Our results reveal that use of illegal drugs had multifaceted, but not illogical, effects.
Keywords:  sentencing; drug abuse; federal sentencing guidelines; substantial assistance departures; pretrial release
Several decades of research demonstrate that the sentencing decision results from a process of gathering and interpreting information about both the offense and the offender. Judges use this information to evaluate the harm done by the crime, the blameworthiness of the offender, and the offender’s potential for reform. As John Hogarth (1971) wrote 40 years ago, sentencing “is a cognitive process in which information concerning the offender, the offense, and the surrounding circumstances is read, organized in relation to other information and integrated into an overall assessment of the case” (p. 279).
This suggests that judges attempt to fashion sentences that fit offenders as well as their crimes. Consistent with the focal-concerns perspective (Steffensmeier, Kramer, & Streifel, 1993; Steffensmeier, Ulmer, & Kramer, 1998), judges are concerned with imposing sentences that not only are proportionate to the seriousness of the crime but also reflect their assessments of offenders’ blameworthiness and future dangerousness. To make these assessments, judges examine the past criminal behavior of offenders as well as their life histories and current circumstances. They may take into consideration such factors as offenders’ educational histories, physical and mental health, history of substance abuse, family and work situations, community ties, and conduct since the arrest as well as the role
