they played in the offense, their motivation for the crime, and the extent to which they feel remorse for their behavior. Assessing offenders in this way “allows judges to make substantial and refined distinctions between offenders who might appear quite similar if one looked only at the legal wrong committed and the harm it caused” (Wheeler, Mann, & Sarat, 1988, p. 120).
The problem with this somewhat idealized view of the sentencing process is that it assumes that judges have discretion to consider offenders’ life histories and current circumstances. However, a series of sentencing reforms implemented during the past four decades—presumptive sentencing guidelines, mandatory minimum sentences, truth-insentencing laws, and “three-strikes-and-you’re-out” habitual offender laws—has curtailed the discretion of judges to take these factors into consideration. For example, the federal sentencing guidelines require the judge to impose a sentence within a range that is determined by the offender’s criminal history and offense seriousness scores.1 Although the guidelines allow judges to depart either upward or downward from the sentence range if the case involves unusual circumstances, there are very limited grounds for these departures. The Federal Sentencing Guidelines Manual (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2008) also spells out the factors that judges are not to take into account in determining the sentence. In accordance with congressional directive, the guidelines state that the offender’s race, gender, national origin, creed, religion, and socioeconomic status are never relevant to the determination of the sentence. Moreover, certain offender characteristics, including the offender’s age, education and vocational skills, employment record, family ties and responsibilities, drug or alcohol abuse, and community ties “are not ordinarily relevant” in determining whether a departure is warranted (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2008, § 5H1.10). These provisions preclude federal judges—at least in theory—from considering what many regard as the “commonsense bases for distinguishing among offenders” (Tonry, 1996, p. 77).
In the current study, the first to address this issue in the context of the federal sentencing process, we focus on the direct and indirect effects of an offender’s substance abuse history on the length of the prison sentence. Using data on drug trafficking offenders adjudicated in three U.S. district courts, we ask whether the offender’s history of nonmarijuana (i.e., “hard”) drug use and use of such drugs at the time of the crime affect the severity of the sentence imposed. We focus on offender substance abuse as a key extralegal factor in sentencing decisions for several reasons. First, substance abuse is a common factor in both drug and nondrug crime, with large majorities of federal offenders charged with drug-related crime or regular users of hard drugs (Belenko & Peugh, 1998; Mumola & Karberg, 2006). Second, much of the impetus for mandatory minimum sentences and other limits to judicial sentencing discretion arose, beginning in the mid-1980s, from concerns about the spread of crack cocaine use, other drug use, and the relationship between hard drug use and other crime (Belenko, 1993; Blumstein & Beck, 1999; Travis, Solomon, & Waul, 2001). Third, despite the media and political portrayal of convicted federal drug traffickers as high-level drug “kingpins,” a majority of convicted traffickers in the federal court system actually play nonmanagerial, relatively minor roles in drug distribution, such as street dealer, courier, bodyguard, lookout, or driver (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2007). Finally, more recent trends in sentencing laws, coupled with the spread of drug treatment alternatives to prison, point to a growing recognition at all levels of the sentencing process that drug abuse and dependence may represent mitigating factors to consider in sentencing decisions, even for drug traffickers (Hora, Schma, & Rosenthal, 1999; Marlowe, 2003; Taxman, Henderson, & Belenko, 2009).

