We also examine whether these substance abuse variables affect sentence severity indirectly through their effects on the likelihood of pretrial detention and the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure. We focus on pretrial detention because judges are required to take the offender’s substance abuse history into account in deciding between detention and release, and we focus on substantial assistance departures, given the discretionary nature of these decisions, which involve both prosecutors and judges, and the potential for offender characteristics, such as substance abuse history, to come into play. Moreover, prior research has shown that both pretrial detention (Johnson & Betsinger, 2009; Spohn, 2009; Ulmer, Eisenstein, & Johnson, 2010) and receipt of a substantial assistance departure (Albonetti, 1997; 2002; Everett & Wojtkiewicz, 2002; Hartley, Maddan, & Spohn, 2007; Johnson, Ulmer, & Kramer, 2008; Kempf-Leonard & Sample, 2001; LaFrenz & Spohn, 2006; Maxfield & Kramer, 1998; Mustard, 2001; Spohn & Fornango, 2009; Steffensmeier & Demuth, 2000; Stacey & Spohn, 2006) are powerful predictors of sentence severity.
Drug Use and the Federal Sentencing Process
As noted above, the Federal Sentencing Guidelines Manual states that “drug or alcohol dependence or abuse is not a reason for imposing a sentence below the guidelines” (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2008, § 5H1.4; emphasis added). In determining the appropriate sentence, in other words, judges are precluded from considering whether the offender has a history of drug abuse or was using drugs at the time of the crime. Although this would seem to rule out mitigated (or aggravated) sentences for drug-addicted offenders, the situation is complicated by the existence of the substantial assistance departure (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2008, § 5K.1.1), which involves discretionary decisions by both prosecutors and judges. Defendants who provide “substantial assistance”—that is, information that leads to the prosecution and conviction of another offender—are eligible for this type of prosecutor-initiated downward departure. Because the meaning of substantial assistance is not defined, and because there are few, if any, guidelines regarding the factors that assistant U.S. attorneys (AUSAs) are to take into account in deciding whether to file a motion for a substantial assistance departure, the decision is highly discretionary.
The discretionary nature of the substantial assistance departure is further illustrated by the fact that if the court grants the motion, the sentencing judge has discretion to determine the amount of the sentence reduction. Section 5K1.1 states that the judge’s decision regarding the appropriate reduction may rest on the significance and usefulness of the defendant’s assistance; the truthfulness, completeness, and reliability of the information provided; the nature, extent, and timeliness of the defendant’s assistance; and any danger or risk that resulted from the defendant’s assistance. Consideration of these factors may result in a sentence that is substantially shorter than the presumptive sentence indicated in the sentencing guidelines; it may even result in a sentence that is shorter than the mandatory minimum sentence that would be applicable absent the downward departure for providing substantial assistance (see 18 U.S.C. § 3553 (e)).
The discretion inherent in the substantial assistance departure opens the door for consideration of offender characteristics, including history of substance abuse, that federal judges are precluded from considering at sentencing. In fact, sentencing scholars contend that substantial assistance departure decisions are a “wellspring of sentencing disparity” (Stith

