& Cabranes, 1998, p. 140) and have the potential to produce the type of unwarranted disparity that the guidelines were intended to eliminate (Kramer & Ulmer, 1996; Mustard, 2001; Nagel & Schulhofer, 1992).
The situation is further complicated in that offender characteristics, including the history of substance abuse, are explicitly relevant to bail and pretrial detention decisions. Pretrial detention decisions in federal courts are structured by the Bail Reform Act of 1984 (2006), which permits judges to detain a defendant as a means of ensuring the safety of the community and the appearance of the defendant in court. Section 3142(b) of the act states that the defendant must be released on personal recognizance or unsecured personal bond unless the judicial officer determines “that such release will not reasonably assure the appearance of the person as required or will endanger the safety of any other person or the community.”
Section 3142(g) specifies the factors that judges must take into consideration in making decisions regarding pretrial release or detention: (a) the nature and circumstances of the offense charged, including whether the offense is a crime of violence or involves a narcotic drug; (b) the weight of the evidence against the defendant; (c) the history and characteristics of the defendant; and (d) the nature and seriousness of the danger to any person or the community that would be posed by the defendant’s release. Included in “the history and characteristics” of the defendant are the defendant’s “character, physical and mental condition, family ties, employment, financial resources, length of residence in the community, community ties, past conduct, history relating to drug or alcohol abuse, criminal history, and record concerning appearance at court proceedings “ (Bail Reform Act of 1984, 2006, § 3142[a][3][A]; emphasis added).
Depending on the decision point, then, an offender’s history of drug use or drug use at the time of the crime may or may not be legally relevant. Judges are instructed to take the defendant’s drug abuse history into account in deciding whether the defendant should be detained pending trial but are precluded from considering this factor in deciding whether the sentence should be outside the applicable guideline range. The offender’s history of drug abuse is not specifically mentioned in the section of the guidelines manual that addresses substantial assistance departures. However, the fact that the guidelines do not define substantial assistance or spell out when a substantial assistance departure is warranted means that the defendant’s substance abuse might come into play in this highly discretionary decision. Coupled with the fact that the sentencing process—even in jurisdictions with presumptive guidelines—is inherently discretionary, the ambivalence and ambiguity surrounding the potential influence of an offender’s drug use history suggest that this factor may come into play as judges attempt to tailor sentences to fit offenders as well as their crimes.
In the sections that follow, we provide a brief review of the literature on four topics: the relationship between drug use or abuse and crime, pretrial detention decisions, substantial assistance departures, and sentencing decisions indicated in the guidelines.
Drug Use or Abuse and Crime
Use and abuse of illegal drugs are extremely common among inmates in U.S. federal prisons. More than three fourths (78.7%) have ever used an illegal drug, 64.3% have used drugs regularly, and nearly half (45.5%) meet diagnostic criteria for drug abuse or dependence (Belenko & Peugh, 2005; Mumola & Karberg, 2006). Aside from marijuana, the most common drugs ever used by federal inmates are cocaine or crack (43.3%), hallucinogens

