(25.9%), methamphetamines (17.9%), or heroin or other opiates (17.9%) (Mumola & Karberg, 2006). Among federal inmates convicted of drug offenses (mainly trafficking), nearly two thirds (62.2%) meet diagnostic criteria for drug abuse or dependence (Mumola & Karberg, 2006).
These statistics reflect both the strong connections between illegal drug use and criminal behavior and the changes in law enforcement practices and sentencing laws that began in the 1980s. The promulgation of the “War on Drugs” in both federal and state criminal justice systems accelerated in the mid-1980s with the emergence of crack cocaine and concerns about violence related to street-level drug markets (Belenko, 1993; Mauer & King, 2007; Tonry, 1995). With passage of the federal Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and 1988, mandatory and lengthier sentences for both drug possession and drug trafficking were implemented in the federal courts. In addition, these laws affected federal sentencing policies for drug cases by providing for lengthier sentences for those convicted of offenses related to crack compared with powder cocaine. Although this sentencing disparity was recently reduced by the U.S. Congress from 100:1 to 18:1 (Fair Sentencing Act of 2010), there remains a highly punitive legacy against crack-related offenses in the federal courts relative to offenses involving other drugs (U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2007).
Although the punitive drug sentencing laws and policies that structure sentencing decisions for drug sellers and users prosecuted in the federal system would seem to preclude consideration of offenders’ drug use history, the recent emergence of a more rehabilitative model of punishment for drug offenders (Belenko, 2002; Belenko, Houser, & Welsh, 2011; Belenko, Sung, Swern, & Donhauser, 2008; Chandler, Fletcher, & Volkow, 2009; Hora et al., 1999; Inciardi, Martin, & Butzin, 2004; Marlowe, 2003; Pelissier et al., 2001) suggests that this factor may come into play. As indicated earlier, most drug traffickers in federal prisons are also drug users (although not necessarily hard drug users), and nearly two thirds meet diagnostic criteria for drug abuse or dependence. Accordingly, discretionary prosecutorial and judicial decisions about pretrial detention, and to some extent, substantial assistance departures, are likely to be affected by information about the offender’s drug use. Sentencing theories (especially focal-concerns theory) suggest that information about an offender, and his or her potential for reform and rehabilitation, is likely to be an important factor in case processing and sentencing decisions. In the case of drug abuse in particular, decision makers’ views about the nature and causes of drug abuse and addiction, the effectiveness of drug treatment, and the causal role of drug use in criminal behavior are likely to affect sentencing and related decisions. These beliefs, and the types of information about the offender’s drug abuse history contained in court records, may affect perceptions of culpability, perceived danger, and rehabilitative potential.
For example, internalized perceptions of theories of drug abuse may affect the level of punitive responses by judges and prosecutors. Theories of addiction as a behavioral or moral issue suggest that (a) personal choice plays an important role in initiating and sustaining drug use, (b) drug abusers can stop or control their use but choose not to, (c) recidivism is highly likely among drug users, and (d) drug abuse is just another indicator of general deviance (Satel, 2007; Sullum, 2003). Thus, those who view addiction as a moral or behavioral issue, with drug use in the person’s control, may be more likely to view such offenders as being culpable for their crimes, more dangerous to society, unlikely to be helped by drug treatment, and needing to be incapacitated to protect society.

