In contrast, the medical or disease model (now widely accepted in the scientific community) posits that drugs (especially opiates and cocaine) directly alter the brain chemistry through their effects on the dopamine reward system. These neurochemical effects—which can last for many months following cessation of drug use—are what cause tolerance and withdrawal symptoms and produce cravings for the drug and make relapse likely (Kosten, 1998; Volkow, Fowler, Wang, Swanson, & Telang, 2007; Volkow & Li, 2005). There is also evidence of a genetic component to drug abuse, with some individuals having a genetic predisposition to the brain effects of drugs (Uhl, 2004; Uhl & Grow, 2004). Judges and prosecutors accepting the disease model of addiction may be more likely to support pretrial release, use of substantial assistance departures, less punitive sentences, or placement into drug treatment programs. In this model, drug trafficking may be viewed as related to the offender’s drug abuse or dependence, thus reducing culpability and increasing the perceived potential for rehabilitation.
Psychodynamic or personality theories of drug abuse suggest that certain personality traits or conditions make people more susceptible to drug abuse (Ball, 2005; Deas, St. Germaine, & Upadhyaya, 2006; Elkins, King, McGue, & Iacono, 2006; Hopwood et al., 2011; Ruiz, Pincus, & Schinka, 2008). These include such traits as risk taking, impulsivity, low self-esteem, or sensitivity to stress. In addition, these theories posit that drug use may be more common among individuals with certain mental health conditions, such as anxiety or depression. Thus, drugs may be used for self-medication to alleviate psychological symptoms and distress, and drug use is more likely to continue if it relieves these symptoms and produces a feeling of well-being (De Bellis, 2002; Sinha, 2001). Acceptance of psychological distress or mental health problems as a causal factor for drug use may make the offender more sympathetic to a judge or prosecutor and may increase the perception that such an individual can be helped with treatment and does not need lengthy incarceration.
Given the violence associated with some drug markets, criminal justice officials’ assessments of defendants who use or sell drugs may also be affected by their perceptions of the relationship between drug use and violent crime. The tripartite conceptual framework proposed by Goldstein (1985) to explain drug-related violence posits three causal explanations: psychopharmacological, economic-compulsive, and systemic. The psychopharmacological model suggests that drugs and violence are strongly and directly connected. According to this model, drugs—especially stimulants, such as cocaine—increase excitability, aggression, hostility, and irrationality, which then increase the likelihood of aggressive or violent behavior (Fagan, 1990; Parker & Auerhahn, 1998). Thus, the psychological and physical effects of psychoactive substances cause users to become violent; absent drug use, the individual would not engage in violent behavior. A variant on this model, disinhibition theory, has been proposed to explain the connections between alcohol use and violence (Fagan, 1990; Parker & Auerhahn, 1998). In the economic-compulsive model, drug users need money to maintain their drug dependence. In the course of committing acquisitive crimes, users engage in behavior (such as robbery and burglary) that can turn violent. Finally, the systemic model posits that drug dealing is inherently confrontational and exploitative and that the social and economic contexts of drug distribution foster aggression and violence (Goldstein, 1985). These can involve “turf wars” among drug dealers or fights with buyers concerning money and reflect the absence of formal structures or mechanisms to resolve disputes among dealers or between dealers and their customers. Generally, data on street drug markets, especially those related to crack and powdered cocaine, support the dominance of the systemic model (Goldstein, 1985).

