To summarize, whether judges and prosecutors view the defendant’s history of drug use or abuse as a mitigating or an aggravating factor may depend on their perceptions of the relationship between drug use or abuse and crime as well as their beliefs about the causal mechanisms that lead individuals to use illegal drugs. Those who see a direct connection between drug use and violent crime and those who believe that drug addiction is a behavioral or moral issue may believe that drug users deserve more punitive treatment. In contrast, those who adopt the medical or disease model or who believe that drug addiction results from personality disorders or mental health issues may be more inclined to mitigate punishment on the basis of the defendant’s history of substance abuse.
Pretrial Detention Decisions in Federal Courts
There is very limited research examining bail and pretrial release and detention decisions in the post–federal guidelines era. This largely reflects that until recently, the publicly available data files from the U.S. Sentencing Commission did not include the offender’s pretrial status. An exception is Spohn’s (2009) analysis of the likelihood of pretrial detention in three federal district courts, which revealed that the offender’s pretrial status was predicted by a mix of offender and case characteristics. The odds of pretrial detention were higher for offenders whose crimes and criminal histories were more serious and for offenders who were under some form of criminal justice control at the time of the offense. Pretrial status also was affected by offenders’ stakes in conformity and community ties: Pretrial detention was less likely for offenders who were more educated, were employed, and/or were married. In addition, Spohn’s study revealed that Black offenders were more likely than White offenders, and male offenders were more likely than female offenders, to be held in custody prior to the sentencing hearing. Research using state-level data (see, e.g., Albonetti, 1991; Albonetti, Hauser, Hagan, & Nagel, 1989; Chiricos & Bales, 1991; Demuth, 2003; Demuth & Steffensmeier, 2004; Katz & Spohn, 1995; Schlesinger, 2005) similarly shows that bail and pretrial release decisions are based primarily on the seriousness of the offense and the defendant’s prior criminal record and ties to the community.
There also is convincing evidence that federal sentence outcomes are affected by pretrial status: Offenders who are detained prior to trial are sentenced more harshly than those who are released (Johnson & Betsinger, 2009; LaFrentz & Spohn, 2006; Spohn, 2009; Ulmer et al., 2010) and are less likely to receive downward or substantial assistance departures (Johnson & Betsinger, 2009; Spohn & Fornango, 2009; Ulmer et al., 2010). This research demonstrates that judges’ pretrial detention decisions in federal courts are based on offender and case characteristics that are generally consistent with the provisions of the Bail Reform Act of 1984. The research also highlights the importance of controlling for pretrial detention in models predicting the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure, the likelihood of incarceration, and the length of the sentence, since being in custody prior to the sentencing hearing has a strong negative effect on the likelihood of departure and a strong positive effect on sentence severity.
Substantial Assistance Departures
There is a growing body of research on the factors that influence the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure and the magnitude of the sentence discount provided to

