offenders who receive these departures. Nagel and Schulhofer (1992), whose qualitative study focused on guideline circumvention in three U.S. district courts in 1989 and 1990, found that substantial assistance departures were used to mitigate the sentences of “salvageable” defendants and that the decisions of AUSAs to file motions for substantial assistance departures were based on their assessments of the value of the case and the sentence that was deserved. Their analysis also revealed that the standards used to determine the type of assistance that qualified as “substantial assistance” varied among the jurisdictions. One jurisdiction had a relatively strict standard that required the defendant to assist in making an arrest and be willing to testify, another had a more flexible standard in which the AUSA would file the motion even when the defendant did not provide information that led to additional prosecutions, and the third had a standard that was relaxed for more sympathetic defendants. Nagel and Schulhofer (1992) concluded that substantial assistance departures were “introducing sentencing disparity and compromising the uniformity and certainty goals of the guidelines” (p. 535).
There is considerable evidence to support Nagel and Schulhofer’s (1992) conclusion that substantial assistance departures are a primary source of unwarranted sentencing disparity. A number of studies reveal that race, ethnicity, and gender affect both the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure and the magnitude of the sentence discount (Albonetti, 1997; 2002; Everett & Wojtkiewicz, 2002; Hartley et al., 2007; Johnson et al., 2008; Kempf-Leonard & Sample, 2001; LaFrenz & Spohn, 2006; Maxfield & Kramer, 1998; Mustard, 2001; Spohn & Fornango, 2009; Stacey & Spohn, 2006; Steffensmeier & Demuth, 2000). For example, Mustard (2001) found that Blacks, Hispanics, males, and those with lower levels of education and income were less likely to receive downward departures—and, when they did, received smaller sentence discounts—than Whites, females, and offenders with higher levels of education and income. Steffensmeier and Demuth (2000) similarly found that Hispanic drug offenders received smaller sentence discounts for providing substantial assistance than did either Black or White drug offenders. Albonetti’s (2002) research revealed that White females received the greatest benefit from substantial assistance departures, and Stacey and Spohn (2006) found that female offenders with children were significantly more likely than female offenders without children to receive a downward departure for providing substantial assistance. As Steffensmeier and Demuth (2000) noted, these findings clearly raise concerns about “the equal application of the law and the wherewithal of the sentencing guidelines in reducing sentencing disparities of any kind” (p. 725).
There also is an emerging body of empirical research confirming that the use of substantial assistance departures varies across court contexts (Hartley et al., 2007; Johnson et al., 2008; Maxfield & Kramer, 1998; Spohn, 2005; Ulmer, 2005; U.S. Sentencing Commission, 2004) and across prosecutors (Spohn & Fornango, 2009). Hartley and his colleagues (2007) found that use of substantial assistance departures for offenders charged with crack and powder cocaine offenses varied significantly across federal circuits, and Maxfield and Kramer (1998) concluded that use of these departures varied across district courts (see also LaCasse & Payne, 1999; Spohn, 2005; and Ulmer, 2005, who found significant differences across district courts). More recently, Johnson et al. (2008) used a multilevel modeling strategy to investigate whether districts varied in their use of sentencing departures. They found significant district-level differences in the likelihood of substantial assistance departures and in the weight attached to the various predictors of these decisions; they also found

