that differences in district courts’ use of substantial assistance departures could be attributed in part to the size of the district’s caseload and the racial composition of the district’s population. Spohn and Fornango (2009) used a similar modeling strategy to examine whether U.S. attorneys varied in their use of substantial assistance departures. They found that although the between-prosecutor differences in the likelihood of obtaining a departure largely reflected differences in the types of cases and the types of offenders handled by each prosecutor, small, but statistically significant, differences across prosecutors remained even after controlling for offender and case characteristics and for the district in which the case was adjudicated. These findings led them to conclude that the prosecutors in the district courts they examined “do not have identical views of the circumstances that justify a substantial assistance departure” (Spohn & Fornango, 2009, pp. 835-836; emphasis in the original).
The research conducted to date, then, reveals that legally irrelevant factors affect the likelihood of receiving substantial assistance departures and the magnitude of the sentence discount. Research also reveals that there is significant intercircuit, interdistrict, and interprosecutor variation in the use of substantial assistance departures, which Johnson et al.’s (2008) study suggests can be at least partially attributed to court contextual factors.
Sentence Outcomes
Research on sentencing outcomes in the postguidelines era focuses on the issue of unwarranted disparity in sentencing, with a particular focus on racial and ethnic disparities. This research generally reveals that unwarranted disparity has not been eliminated. For example, Spohn (2000) reviewed 40 studies examining the relationship between race, ethnicity, and sentencing. This included 32 studies of sentencing decisions at the state level and 8 studies at the federal level. Consistent with the conclusions of earlier reviews (Chiricos & Crawford, 1995), Spohn reported that many of these studies revealed a direct race effect. At both the state and federal levels, there was evidence that African Americans and Hispanics were more likely than Whites to be sentenced to prison; at the federal level, there was also evidence that African Americans received longer sentences than Whites. These findings are confirmed by several more recent studies of state and federal sentencing decisions (Everett & Wojtkiewicz, 2002; Johnson & Betsinger, 2009; Kempf-Leonard & Sample, 2001; Kramer & Steffensmeier, 1993; Mustard, 2001; Pasko, 2002; Spohn & Holleran, 2000; Steffensmeier & Demuth, 2000; Steffensmeier et al., 1998; Ulmer et al., 2010). For example, Steffensmeier and Demuth (2000), who compared sentence outcomes for Whites, Blacks, White Hispanics, and Black Hispanics, found that the likelihood of incarceration was substantially lower and the mean prison sentence significantly shorter for White offenders than for minorities, especially Hispanics.
There also is substantial evidence that the gender of the offender influences state and federal sentence outcomes. In fact, a report on the first 15 years of federal guidelines sentencing by the U.S. Sentencing Commission (2004) stated that “the gap in average prison terms between male and female offenders has widened in the guidelines era” (p. 127). Consistent with this, a number of studies found that female offenders were sentenced more leniently than male offenders (Albonetti, 1997, 2002; Everett & Wojtkiewicz, 2002; Johnson & Betsinger, 2009; Mustard, 2001; Steffensmeier et al., 1993; Ulmer et al., 2010). The results of these studies, all of which controlled for crime seriousness, the offender’s

