criminal history, and other legally relevant factors, clearly suggest that judges evaluate female offenders differently than male offenders.
Only a handful of sentencing studies have examined the interaction of race or ethnicity and other extralegal variables; the research that does exist demonstrates that offender characteristics have both indirect and interactive effects on federal sentence outcomes. Albonetti’s (1997) research on drug offenders, for example, revealed that the offender’s gender affected sentencing decisions for White offenders and Black offenders but not for Hispanic offenders and that gender and race or ethnicity conditioned the effects of guideline departures, guilty pleas, offense seriousness, and criminal history (see also Brennan & Spohn, 2009; Spohn & Brennan, 2011). In a later study, Albonetti (2002) found that White females received the greatest benefit from substantial assistance departures and that the guideline offense level had a more pronounced effect on sentence length for White females than for Black females. LaFrentz and Spohn (2006), whose research revealed that race and ethnicity did not have a direct effect on sentence length, found that race and ethnicity interacted with gender and employment status. Black and Hispanic females got shorter sentences than their male counterparts, but White females were treated no differently than White males, and unemployed Whites received longer sentences than employed Whites, but there were no differences in the sentences imposed on unemployed and employed Blacks and Hispanics. Research in the state courts similarly suggests that young Black and Hispanic males pay a punishment penalty (Spohn & Holleran, 2000; Steffensmeier et al., 1998).
In summary, research on the sentencing process suggests that structured sentencing reforms have not been able to achieve the goal of eliminating unwarranted disparity in sentencing. Sentence outcomes in the postguidelines era are affected by the legally irrelevant offender characteristics, including race, ethnicity, and gender.
The Current Study
The purpose of this study is to determine whether the offender’s history of hard drug use and hard drug use at the time of the crime affect case outcomes for offenders charged with and convicted of drug trafficking offenses in three federal district courts. We focus on three outcomes: whether the offender was in pretrial detention prior to adjudication, whether the offender received a downward departure for providing substantial assistance, and the length of the sentence imposed on offenders who were sentenced to prison. We do not test specific hypotheses about the relationships between drug use or drug use history and these outcomes. As noted earlier, decision makers’ views about the nature and causes of drug abuse and addiction, the effectiveness of drug treatment, and the causal role of drug use in criminal (especially violent) behavior are likely to affect their perceptions of drug offenders’ dangerousness, culpability, and potential for rehabilitation. Prosecutors and judges who see a direct connection between drug use and violent crime or who believe that drug addiction is a behavioral or moral choice, with drug use in the person’s control, may believe that those who use drugs are more culpable, dangerous, and likely to recidivate and that they therefore deserve more punitive treatment. In contrast, prosecutors and judges who adopt the medical or disease model or who believe that drug addiction results from personality disorders or mental health issues may have more sympathetic views of offenders with a history of substance use and, as a result, may treat them more leniently when making decisions regarding pretrial detention, substantial assistance departures, and sentence length.

