Method
Data
We used a subset of data collected for a study of charging and sentencing decisions in three U.S. district courts: the District of Minnesota, the District of Nebraska, and the Southern District of Iowa. The data file includes detailed information on all offenders sentenced in these courts during fiscal years 1998, 1999, and 2000.2 For this study, we selected all cases for which the offender was convicted of a drug trafficking offense.3 We eliminated cases (n = 25) with offenders who were Asian or Native American as well as cases with missing data on the independent variables. This resulted in a data file with 1,567 cases: 558 from the Southern District of Iowa, 450 from the District of Minnesota, and 579 from the District of Nebraska.
We use the data from these three district courts, rather than data from all U.S. district courts, for two reasons. First, the primary independent variables for this study—whether the offender had a history of hard drug use and whether the offender was using hard drugs at the time of the crime—are not included in the publicly available data files from the U.S. Sentencing Commission. Because we had access to the presentence reports in these three district courts, we were able to collect this information. Second, there is mounting evidence that sentence outcomes vary significantly among federal district courts (Hofer, Blackwell, & Ruback, 1999; Kautt, 2002; LaCasse & Payne, 1999; Spohn, 2005). This calls into question the conclusions of studies of federal sentencing decisions that use data aggregated across all district courts. As Weisselberg and Dunworth (1993) noted, “it is extremely difficult, and perhaps unhelpful, to draw general, system-wide conclusions about the effect of the guidelines upon the district courts” (p. 27). Because of these concerns, we use data from three relatively homogeneous U.S. district courts, and we control for the district in which the case was adjudicated.
Dependent and Independent Variables
Descriptive statistics for the dependent and independent variables are presented in Table 1. There are three dependent variables. The first is a dichotomous measure of whether the offender was detained (coded 1) or released (coded 0) prior to adjudication (by plea or by trial). The second is a dichotomous variable indicating whether the offender received a downward departure for providing substantial assistance (yes = 1; no = 0). The third dependent variable is the length of the prison sentence imposed on offenders who were sentenced to prison. (There were only 33 offenders convicted of drug trafficking offenses who were not sentenced to prison; therefore, we do not model the likelihood of a prison sentence.) Because the values were positively skewed, we logged the sentence length variable. In these three district courts, 63.9% of the offenders were in custody prior to adjudication, 38.3% of the offenders received substantial assistance departures, and the mean sentence was 90.45 months.
The primary independent variables are indicators of the offender’s drug use or abuse, which is measured by three dummy variables: whether the offender had a history of hard drug use but was not using drugs at the time of the crime (yes = 1; no = 0); whether the offender was under the influence of hard drugs at the time of the crime (yes = 1; no = 0), and whether the offender had never used hard drugs (yes = 1; no = 0), which is the

