not using drugs at the time of the crime, offenders who were using hard drugs at the time of the crime, and offenders who had never used hard drugs As indicated earlier, we define “hard drugs” as powder cocaine, crack cocaine, methamphetamine, and heroin and other opiates. Information on the offender’s drug use was obtained during the presentence investigation (either from the offender or from family members and other individuals interviewed during the investigation) and documented in the presentence report. (We were unable to measure the frequency of hard drug use, as the presentence investigation report did not include this information.)
As shown in Table 1, substantial percentages of these drug trafficking offenders had a history of hard drug use but were not using drugs at the time of the crime (22.1%) or were under the influence of hard drugs at the time of the crime (51.4%); only 26.4% of the offenders had no current or past history of hard drug use. Further analysis revealed that many offenders had a history of using more than one type of drug and that some were under the influence of more than one drug at the time of the crime. The most common type of drug ever used was powder cocaine (61.1% of offenders reported using this drug), followed by methamphetamine (44.6%), crack cocaine (20.3%), and heroin (7.4%). Approximately one third (31.1%) of the offenders reported that they were under the influence of methamphetamine at the time of crime, and one fourth (24.5%) reported being under the influence of powder cocaine. In contrast, very few offenders reported being under the influence of either crack cocaine (7.7%) or heroin (1.6%) at the time of the crime.
All analyses also control for the offender’s race or ethnicity and gender and for other offender and case characteristics shown by previous research to influence federal sentencing or pretrial release decisions. Race and ethnicity are measured with three dummy variables (Black, Hispanic, and White); White offenders are the reference category. The offender’s gender is measured with a dichotomous variable (female = 1; male = 0). We also include dummy variables for the offender’s employment status (employed = 1; unemployed = 0), citizenship status (U.S. citizen = 1; noncitizen = 0), and marital status (married = 1; not married = 0). We also control for the offender’s number of dependent children and for the number of criminal history points assigned to the offender, which ranges from 0 to 44. Three dummy variables are included to measure the offender’s educational achievement (no high school degree, high school degree, some college or college degree), with those holding less than a high school degree as the reference category. The offender’s age is a ratio-level variable that measures the offender’s age in years.
We control for several case characteristics, which differ somewhat depending on the dependent variable being analyzed. All analyses include the presumptive sentence, which, like the actual sentence, is positively skewed and is therefore logged. Other case characteristics included in all of the models are dichotomous indicators of whether the most serious charge against the offender was a drug conspiracy charge (yes = 1; no = 0) and whether the offender was under some type of criminal justice control (out on bail, on probation, on parole) at the time of the crime (yes = 1; no = 0). We also control for the type of drug involved in the offense, measured by four dummy variables (powder cocaine, crack cocaine, and methamphetamine, with other drugs as the reference category), whether the offender received an adjustment to the presumptive sentence for playing an aggravated role or mitigated role in the offense (no role adjustment is the reference category), and the jurisdiction in which the case was adjudicated (Minnesota and Nebraska, with southern Iowa as the reference category). Our analysis of sentence length also controls for whether the offender

