received a downward departure for providing substantial assistance (yes = 1; no = 0) or a regular downward departure (yes = 1; no = 0). Our analyses of the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure and sentence length include whether the offender was in custody prior to adjudication (in custody = 1; released = 0).
Although prior research on federal sentence outcomes controlled for the offense seriousness score and the offender’s criminal history score, the present study controls for the presumptive sentence, which is the approach recommended by Engen and Gainey (2000) and the U.S. Sentencing Commission (2004). The presumptive sentence, based on the offense seriousness score and the criminal history score, is the minimum sentence that that judge could impose without departing from the guidelines. To account for mandatory minimum sentences that were prevalent in drug trafficking cases, we measure the presumptive sentence as the guideline minimum unless a mandatory minimum sentence was triggered and indicated a longer sentence than the guideline minimum. In such cases, the presumptive sentence is measured as the mandatory minimum sentence. If there was a mandatory minimum sentence but the safety valve was applied, the presumptive sentence is the guideline minimum.
The data displayed in Table 1 reveal that three quarters of the offenders adjudicated in these three U.S. district courts were either White (41.6%) or Hispanic (32.5%); 25.8% were Black. Most offenders (84.7%) were male and their average age was approximately 32 years old. The typical offender had at least one dependent child, was employed at the time of the offense, was a U.S citizen, had not attended college, and was not married. The mean number of criminal history points assigned to these offenders was 4.28, indicating that most of these offenders had relatively minimal criminal histories (the maximum number of points is 44).
The mean presumptive sentence was 116.42 months, and three quarters (76.4%) of the offenders were facing drug conspiracy charges. More than half (53.8%) of the offenders adjudicated in these three district courts were convicted of an offense involving methamphetamine; most of the remaining offenders were convicted of an offense involving either crack (22.5%) or powder (13.8%) cocaine. Almost two thirds (63.9%) of the offenders were in custody prior to adjudication, and approximately one third (34.8%) were under criminal justice control at the time of the crime. Most offenders did not receive either an aggravated (8.5%) or a mitigated (18.4%) role adjustment.
We use binary logistic regression to analyze the likelihood of pretrial detention and the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure, which are dichotomous variables, and ordinary least squares regression to analyze the length of the sentence (logged).
Results
The results of our analysis of the likelihood of pretrial detention, which are presented in Table 2, provide mixed support for our hypothesis that the offender’s history of drug use and drug use at the time of the crime would have positive effects on the odds of detention. Consistent with our hypothesis, offenders who were using hard drugs at the time of the crime were nearly two times (Exp[b] = 1.98) more likely to be in custody prior to adjudication than offenders who had no history of hard drug use. On the other hand, the odds of pretrial detention for offenders with a history of hard drug use but who were not using drugs at the time of the crime did not differ from those for offenders who had never used hard drugs.

