Not surprisingly, the odds of pretrial detention were affected by the seriousness of the offense and the offender’s criminal history (as measured by the presumptive sentence) and by other legally relevant factors. Offenders who played a major role in the drug trafficking offense (and thus received an aggravated role adjustment to the offense severity score) were more likely to be detained, as were those who were under some type of criminal justice control at the time of the crime. A somewhat counterintuitive finding is that drug offenders whose crimes involved methamphetamine were less likely to be detained than those whose crimes involved marijuana, heroin, or other drugs. In addition, the odds of pretrial detention were affected by the jurisdiction in which the case adjudicated; offenders in Nebraska and Minnesota were less likely than those in southern Iowa to be in custody prior to adjudication.

