The likelihood of pretrial detention also was affected by several offender characteristics in addition to the offender’s use of drugs at the time of the crime, including the offender’s race, ethnicity, gender, employment status, citizenship status, marital status, and education. The odds of pretrial detention were higher for Black and Hispanic offenders than for White offenders, for unemployed offenders than for those who were employed, and for noncitizens than for citizens; in contrast, the likelihood of detention was lower for females than for males, for married offenders than for those who were unmarried, and for offenders with some college or a college degree than for those without a high school degree.
Although some of these are factors that judges are required to take into consideration when deciding whether the offender should be released or not (i.e., the offender’s employment status, marital status, education, and citizenship status), others—especially the offender’s race or ethnicity and gender—should not influence the likelihood of pretrial detention after offense seriousness and other legally relevant factors are taken into consideration. The fact that these legally irrelevant factors did have a direct effect on pretrial detention suggests that, consistent with the focal-concerns perspective, they are linked to judges’ attributions of dangerousness, threat, and likelihood of nonappearance at court proceedings.
Our second hypothesis predicted that the offender’s history of drug use and drug use at the time of the crime would affect the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure, but we did not predict the direction of the relationship. As shown in Table 3, the odds of a substantial assistance departure were affected by both drug-use variables. Compared to offenders who reported that they had never used hard drugs, those with a history of drug use and those who were using drugs during the commission of the crime were more likely to receive a downward departure for providing substantial assistance.
Consistent with the results for pretrial detention, the likelihood of a substantial assistance departure was affected by a mix of offender and case characteristics. Although the offender’s race and ethnicity did not have significant effects, the odds of receiving a departure were higher for female offenders than for male offenders and for offenders with some college or a college degree than for offenders without a high school degree; the odds were lower for noncitizens than for citizens. Whereas offenders facing longer presumptive sentences and those charged with a drug trafficking conspiracy were more likely to receive a departure, offenders who played a major role in the offense had lower odds, as did offenders who were in custody during the pretrial process. Finally, offenders adjudicated in Nebraska and Minnesota were less likely than those adjudicated in southern Iowa to receive a substantial assistance departure.
