In contrast, both the offender’s history of hard drug use and his or her use of drugs at the time of the crime led to a higher likelihood that the offender would receive a substantial assistance departure, which led in turn to a substantially shorter sentence. Thus, offenders with a history of hard drug use—regardless of whether they were using drugs at the time of the crime—received shorter sentences than offenders without a history of drug use because of the fact that they were more likely than offenders with no drug-use history to receive downward departures for providing substantial assistance. There also is a more complex path from history of drug use—again regardless of whether the offender was using drugs at the time of the crime—to a higher likelihood of pretrial detention to a lower likelihood of a substantial assistance departure and to a harsher sentence. We explore the implications of these findings in the next section.

Discussion
Our study revealed that use of illegal drugs had multifaceted effects on outcomes for drugtrafficking offenders sentenced according to the federal sentencing guidelines. Whereas offenders with a history of illegal drug use and offenders using drugs at the time of the crime had a higher likelihood of receiving a substantial assistance departure, offenders using drugs at the time of the crime had a lower likelihood of pretrial release. Neither drug-use variable had a direct effect on the length of the sentence imposed by the judge. These inconsistencies are not necessarily at odds with the rules and regulations that govern these decisions. That neither druguse variable had a direct effect on sentence length means that judges are following the guidelines, in that the history of substance abuse is not “ordinarily relevant” to the determination of the appropriate sentence. Similarly, judges are supposed to take the offender’s illegal drug use into account in making bail and pretrial release decisions, and the discretion inherent in prosecutors’ decisions regarding substantial assistance departures opens the door for consideration of issues such as substance abuse. These decisions are likely to be affected by whether decision makers view drug abuse as a disease, psychological disorder, or moral or behavior issue.

Spohn, Belenko / DO THE DRUGS, DO THE TIME?   665
The fact that substance abuse had a negative effect on pretrial release but a positive effect on a substantial assistance departure is also logical, given the objectives of judges and prosecutors when making these decisions. Although we can only speculate, our findings suggest that judges view offenders who were using drugs at the time of the crime as likely to continue to participate in drug trafficking to support their use and as unlikely to show up for all court appearances; as a result, judges view these offenders as high risks for recidivism and poor risks for pretrial release. In contrast, prosecutors appear to regard drugabusing offenders (whether measured by a history of illegal drug use or by use of drugs at the time of the crime) as more sympathetic and less culpable and, thus, as better candidates for substantial assistance departures. It may be that prosecutors believe that the severe penalties for drug trafficking are inappropriately harsh for drug-abusing offenders who may be engaging in drug distribution simply as a means of securing drugs for their personal use. This belief would be more likely if prosecutors view drug abuse as a brain disease rather than being in the control of the individual.
Our findings highlight the importance of examining outcomes other than the sentence length as well as the need to test for indirect as well as direct effects. Had we simply examined the effects of drug use on sentence length, we would have concluded that the offender’s current and past use of illegal drugs did not affect punishment. This conclusion would have been misleading, given our findings regarding the effects of drug use on pretrial detention and substantial assistance departures and the subsequent effects of pretrial detention and receipt of a departure on sentence length. Both drug-use variables affected sentence length indirectly through their effects of the likelihood of pretrial detention and substantial assistance departure.
The findings also point to the importance of the jurisdiction in which the case was adjudicated. Although we examined case outcomes in three relatively homogenous district courts, we found that all three case outcomes varied significantly by jurisdiction. Compared to offenders adjudicated in the Southern District of Iowa, offenders whose cases were processed in the District of Minnesota and the District of Nebraska were less likely to be detained prior to trial and less likely to receive substantial assistance departures; they also received significantly shorter sentences. These jurisdictional differences are not surprising. Interviews with criminal justice officials in each of these jurisdictions revealed that the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of Iowa at the time these data were collected exercised less oversight over and had a looser policy regarding the use of substantial assistance departures and that judges in this jurisdiction had more liberal attitudes toward using departures to reduce sentences. The interviews also revealed that officials in southern Iowa were more supportive of the federal sentencing guidelines generally. This lends credence to researchers’ contention that aggregating data across all district courts may distort the reality of decision making in each district court (Kautt, 2002; LaCasse & Payne, 1999; Spohn, 2005).
Limitations
There are several limitations to our study that should be noted. Our data were from three federal court districts in the midwestern United States, and thus the findings may not be generalizable to other districts. In particular, the prevalence of methamphetamine use is higher than in most other federal court districts. In addition, the data comprise court cases that were sentenced between 1998 and 2000; thus recent changes in U.S. sentencing guidelines, such as the Booker decision, and the reduction in the crack cocaine sentencing disparity may have

666   Criminal Justice and Behavior
had effects on the relationship between drug use and pretrial or sentencing decisions for drug traffickers.
Our measures of drug use are based on presentence investigation reports and thus are not clinical diagnoses of drug abuse or dependence. However, because the drug-use data are from these reports, they do accurately reflect the information that would have been available to the judges and prosecutors at the time their decisions were made. On the other hand, it is possible that other information not contained in the data set (such as information about the offender presented by his or her defense attorney, witness testimony about the offender’s character) may have been available to prosecutors and judges and incorporated into decision making.
Conclusions and Implications
Our findings advance sentencing research by suggesting that an offenders’ nonmarijuana drug use does affect sentencing decisions but only indirectly by affecting pretrial detention and substantial assistance departure decisions. Accordingly, a more nuanced consideration is needed of the impacts of drug use on crime and sentencing decisions, including granting of substantial assistance departures. Given that prosecutors and judges appear to be considering current drug use as an aggravating factor (increasing the likelihood of pretrial detention), it may be important to provide decision makers with better clinical assessments of current and past drug abuse status to inform detention decisions, to assess public safety risk and rehabilitative potential, and to also develop and expand treatment-based alternatives to pretrial detention.
Additional research is needed to disentangle the causal connections between drug abuse and drug trafficking for federal offenders. Our data suggest a seeming contradiction among prosecutors and judges as to whether drug traffickers who also use hard drugs should be viewed as less blameworthy or as an increased public safety risk. Research on judicial and prosecutorial attitudes toward addiction and drug-involved offenders and their views about the causes of drug abuse would help elucidate the ways in which drug-use information is used in case decisions and identify areas in which more training and education for judges and prosecutors are needed about the causes of drug abuse.
Illegal drug use is quite common among offenders in federal court, and a majority of those convicted of drug trafficking have histories of illegal drug use. However, a majority of convicted drug traffickers in federal court play relatively minor roles in the drug distribution process. With the goal of developing more informed sentencing decisions for drug offenders that protect public safety, achieve just and fair sentencing goals, and maximize the use of rehabilitative interventions to reduce drug-related crime, it is important to continue to examine the role that drug use plays in pretrial detention and sentencing decisions in the federal courts.
